    {{#inertia}}




Consider the rectangular prism W, [{{x1}}, {{x2}}]\times[{{y1}}, {{y2}}]\times[{{z1}}, {{z2}}], with density function \delta(x,y,z)={{delt}}.









                Write an integral which computes the mass of this prism.







                    The mass is found by:
                    \displaystyle \iiint_W {{delta}} dV = \int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} } {{delt}}\ d x\ dy\ dz={{mass}}.









                Write an integral which computes the moment of inertia of this prism about the {{w3}}-axis.








                    I_{ {{w3}} }=\displaystyle \iiint_W ( {{w1}}^2+{{w2}}^2 ){{delta}} dV = \int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} }  ( {{w1}}^2+{{w2}}^2 )({{delt}})\ d x\ dy\ dz={{I}}.









                Use the above to integrals to find an expression for the radius of gyration.







                    r_{ {{w3}} }=\sqrt{\frac{I_{ {{w3}} }}{M}} =\sqrt{
                        \frac{\int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} }  ( {{w1}}^2+{{w2}}^2 )({{delt}})\ d x\ dy\ dz}
                        {\int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} } {{delt}}\ d x\ dy\ dz} }
                        ={{r}}.










    {{/inertia}}



    {{#center}}




Consider the rectangular prism W, [{{x1}}, {{x2}}]\times[{{y1}}, {{y2}}]\times[{{z1}}, {{z2}}], with density function \delta(x,y,z)={{delt}}.









                Write an integral which computes the mass of this prism.







                    The mass is found by:
                    \displaystyle \iiint_W {{delta}} dV = \int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} } {{delt}}\ d x\ dy\ dz={{mass}}.









                Write an integral which computes the total moment with respect to the the {{w1}}{{w2}}-plane.








                    T_{ {{w3}} }=\displaystyle \iiint_W ( {{w1}}^2+{{w2}}^2 ){{delta}} dV = \int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} }  ( {{w3}} )({{delt}})\ d x\ dy\ dz={{T}}.









                Use the above to integrals to find an expression for the {{w3}} coordinate of the center of mass.








                    \bar{ {{w3}} }=\frac{T_{ {{w3}} }}{M} =
                        \frac{\int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} }  ( {{w3}} )({{delt}})\ d x\ dy\ dz}
                        {\int_{ z={{z1}} }^{ z={{z2}} } \int_{y= {{y1}} }^{y= {{y2}} } \int _{ x={{x1}} }^{ x={{x2}} } {{delt}}\ d x\ dy\ dz} 
                        ={{C}}.










